Python Project - Dataset Exploration on Prosper loan¶

by Olayinka Ahmed Ibitowa¶

Introduction¶

This project is part of my Phython Data Analyst degree program. I investigated an Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on a data set from Prosper loan, which is the first America lending platform with over 9 billion dollars in funded loans.

the Data set contains 113,937 rows and 81 columns. Some of the columns are the loan amount, terms, BorrowersRate, employment status etc.

The main purpose of this project is to analyse the data set and summarised my findings for future cusotmer users and also to determine what influences Prosper loan interest rate.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original dataset contains (113937, 81) column. After cleaning and selection of columns of importance, the dataframe now contains (84853, 24) column by rows. The dataframe contains columns such as ProsperScore, DebtToIncomeRatio, LoanOriginalAmount BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, Term etc. Most variables are numeric and categorical in nature.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in finding:

  • What are the main factors affecting the interest rate? What's the average interest rate on big loans?
  • the interest rate applied for small loans? the size of loans do borrowers usually take out from Prosper? Who takes big loans? Who takes small loans?
  • Are there any differences between loans depending on different level of employment status?
  • Which category of listing takes the most loans and for what purpose?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Columns created and selected into the dataframe of df_interest would be used to help investigate the features of my interest. Some of the columns are:

  • IncomeRange
  • DebtToIncomeRatio
  • PosperRating
  • Collateral
  • Employment status
  • Type of CreditCard
  • LoanOriginalAmount

Plotting in bars for better view and visuals as pie are overlapping due to the smaller percentages

In [148]:
# loanstatus_counts = df_interest['LoanStatus'].value_counts() already defined
# since pie chart is not exploding the smaller percentage, I had to use a bar for better viusals

# Calculate percentages
percentages = loanstatus_counts / loanstatus_counts.sum() * 100

# Plot the bar chart
ax = sns.barplot(x=loanstatus_counts.index, y=loanstatus_counts, color='teal')

# Display percentages above the bars
for i, val in enumerate(loanstatus_counts):
    ax.text(i, val, f'{percentages[i]:.1f}%', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=12)

plt.title('Percentage Loan Status Distribution', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Loan Status')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

plt.show()

Results explanation¶

The distribution of the loan status shows about 66.7 percent are currenlty on the loan plan with about 23,2 percent completed. Past Due and defaulted are quite low which indicates the commitment of customers from Prsoper loan.

In [197]:
ax=sns.countplot(x='ProsperScore', data=df_interest, color='lightgreen')
ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0], fmt='%.lf')
plt.xlabel('Risk of Score of Borrower')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Prosper Score Distribution')
plt.show()

Results explanation¶

PrsperScore ranges from 1 to 11 with 11 being the lowest risk and 1 the highest. The results shows that Prosper score has a bell shaped distribution spiking on score with 4, 6 and 8. Fewer customers are within the higest risk of score (1 to 3) and also within the lowest risk of score (9 to 119 while majority of the customer are between 4 and 8.

order_creditgrade = df['CreditGrade'].value_counts().index  # Create an order in descending order

ax = sns.countplot(x='CreditGrade', data=df, color='lightgreen', order=order_creditgrade)

# Calculate the percentage values
total_count = len(df)
percentages = df['CreditGrade'].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100

# Display the percentage values on each bar
for i, val in enumerate(df['CreditGrade'].value_counts()):
    ax.text(i, val, f'{percentages[i]:.1f}%', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=12)

plt.ylabel('count')
plt.xlabel('Credit Grade')
plt.title('Percentage Distribution of Credit Grade')

plt.show()

Results explanation¶

For better comparison, their percentage distribution was analyzed. Credit grade of C being the highest has about 19.5 percent while NC has about 0.5 percent. Other types of credit grade such as AA, A and B are also in a better position. This results explains that customers of Prsoper loan have a better credit grade

In [218]:
# define a classification function
def classify(row):
    if row["StatedMonthlyIncome"]<2500:
        return 'Low'
    if row["StatedMonthlyIncome"]<8000:
        return 'Medium'
    else:
        return 'High'
    
df_interest['WageGroup'] = df_interest.apply(classify, axis=1)

# convert string to ordinal category type and order them
ordinal_class = ['Low', 'Medium', 'High']
ordered_variable = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_class)
df_interest['WageGroup'] = df_interest['WageGroup'].astype(ordered_variable)

# Plot the new variable
sns.countplot(data = df_interest, x = 'WageGroup', color='lightgreen')
plt.title('Wage Group of Montly Income');

Notes¶

Majority of customer from Prosper loan who have taken out credit are in the middle class and have an average monthly salary ranging from 2500 to 8000 dollars.

Notes¶

The CurrentCreditLines and OpenRevolvingAccounts are highly and positively strongly correlated with one another (correlation of 0.853). The other strong relationship is between BorrowRate and BorrowerAPR (correlation of 0.990). There are also moderate and some positive correlation between interest rate and loan amount. Other numerical variables does not show any strong correlation.

In [224]:
# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical/ordinal features.
# use a 2000 sample since there are fewer plots and they're simpler in nature.
df_sample = df_interest.sample(2000, replace=False)

#define boxgrid function
def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color = default_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90);


g = sns.PairGrid(data = df_sample, y_vars = ['BorrowerRate'], x_vars = ['EmploymentStatus','IsBorrowerHomeowner','WageGroup'],
                aspect = 1.5);
g.map(boxgrid);

Notes¶

The results indicates thats unemployed people have a better borrower rate than any other type of jobs.
Also, most borrowers with a high borrower rate are not home owners
Majority of borrowers whose wage group are low have a high borrowers rate.

In [223]:
#define violin function
def violin(x, y, **kwargs):
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.violinplot(x=x, y=y, color = default_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90);
    
g = sns.PairGrid(data = df_sample, y_vars = ['BorrowerRate'], x_vars = ['ProsperScore','ProsperRating (Alpha)'],
                aspect = 1.5);
g.map(violin);

Notes¶

The results shows The influence of ProsperScore and rating on BorrowerRate. It can be easily explained that the lower the PrspoerScore , the higher the BorrowerRates and vice versa. Prosper score of 1.0 would have a BorrowerRate of about 20-40% as compared to a better Score of 11 with about 2-15% r<borrowers ate. Same principle also applies to ProsperRating, A better rating of AA showed lower borrowers rate as compared to HR. And is the rating descends, the borrowers rate increases.

ax = sns.pointplot(
    data=df_interest,
    x='ProsperRating (Alpha)',
    y='BorrowerAPR',
    hue='LoanStatus',
    palette='Greens',
    linestyles='',
    dodge=0.3,

)

plt.ylabel('Borrower APR')
plt.show()

Note¶

This plot shows the influence of Prosper rating and loan status on Borrower APR. Regardless of the loan status, prosper rating plays a better role on borrowers APR. The better the rating (AA to HR), the lesser the APR. For defaulted and charged off loans usually have a higher APR for all prosper rating except for AA and A.

In [271]:
#plot pointplot 
fig = plt.figure(figsize = [8,5])
ax = sns.pointplot(data = df_interest, x = 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', y = 'BorrowerRate', hue = 'Term',
           palette = 'Blues', linestyles = '',dodge = 0.4, ci='sd')

Notes¶

This results indicates the influence of Prosper rating, terms and borrower rates. Prosper rating is dependent on borrowes rate which is dependent on term. This means the better the rating and the shorter the term of payment, the lower the borrower rates. For better rating for example A, the interest is quite small when the term of payment is 12 months. However, as the term increases, the borrowers rate is also increases. All of this is true for all type of rating. HR only has a term payment of only 36 months as compared to all other rating.

Conclusion¶

The datasets was imported and column of interest was selected and assigned a data frame for better analysis. Univariate, Bivariate and Multivariate analysis was perfomed. The following was therefore summarised from the data sets

  • Most customers with a better prosper rating have a lower borrowers APR and borrowers rate.
  • Being a home owner (collateral) plays a major influence in the original loan amount. However, with a better wage group, the loan amount increases more.
  • In parallel, for all Prosper Ratings except for "A",and "AA", Defaulted and charged off loans usually have a higher Borrower APR compared to completed or current loans(good records).
